# Project: WebdriverIO JavaScript Test Automation Framework

## Framework Structure
- Use WebdriverIO as the primary test runner
- Implement Page Object Model pattern with ES6 classes
- Organize specs by feature areas
- Use TypeScript for better type safety and autocompletion
- Keep configuration in wdio.conf.ts

## Coding Standards
- Follow TypeScript best practices
- Use ESLint with WebdriverIO recommended rules
- Maximum line length: 100 characters
- Use async/await for all async operations
- Use meaningful, descriptive selector variables

## Test Organization
- Group tests using describe/it blocks
- Use mocha or jasmine framework based on project needs
- Implement proper test tagging with grep or suite filters
- Create separate config files for local, staging, and production
- Use spec file grouping for parallel execution

## Best Practices
- Prefer user-facing selectors: aria labels, roles, text content
- Use $ and $$ for element queries; avoid raw CSS/XPath when possible
- Use browser.pause() only as a last resort; prefer waitForDisplayed/waitForClickable
- Implement retry logic for flaky network-dependent steps
- Use browser.url() with base URL configuration
- Avoid hardcoded timeouts; configure implicitTimeout globally

## Element Handling
- Use custom $ extensions or page object getters for reusable selectors
- Prefer aria selectors (aria/button[name='Submit']) for accessibility
- Implement waitForDisplayed before interaction with dynamic elements
- Use shadow$ and shadow$$ for Shadow DOM elements
- Handle iframes with browser.switchToFrame() and switchToParentFrame()

## Page Object Model
- Extend a base Page class with common actions (open, waitForLoad)
- Keep selectors as private readonly getters
- Expose only high-level action methods from page objects
- Return the next page object from navigation actions
- Place page objects in test/pageObjects/ directory

## Test Data Management
- Store test data in JSON fixtures or TypeScript constants
- Use environment variables for credentials and environment-specific data
- Use @wdio/shared-store-service for cross-spec data sharing
- Never commit sensitive data; use .env files with dotenv

## Assertions
- Use expect-webdriverio matchers (expect(element).toBeDisplayed())
- Prefer async matchers that have built-in retry logic
- Avoid manual polling loops; let expect-webdriverio handle retries
- Include meaningful failure messages in assertions

## Configuration
- Configure maxInstances for parallel execution
- Set baseUrl in wdio.conf.ts for portability
- Use @wdio/sauce-service or @wdio/browserstack-service for cloud grids
- Enable video/screenshot on failure with afterTest hook
- Use @wdio/allure-reporter or spec reporter for CI-friendly output

## API & Component Testing
- Use browser.call() to run Node.js HTTP requests inside tests
- Use @wdio/browser-runner for component testing (React, Vue, Svelte)
- Separate API helper utilities from UI page objects
- Intercept and mock network requests with browser.mock()

## Mobile Testing
- Use Appium service (@wdio/appium-service) for native mobile automation
- Configure separate wdio.mobile.conf.ts for iOS and Android
- Use mobile$ selectors with accessibility IDs for cross-platform locators
- Implement gesture helpers (swipe, scroll, tap) via @wdio/mobile-utils

## Reporting
- Use Allure Reporter for rich HTML test reports
- Attach screenshots on failure via afterTest hook
- Integrate with CI/CD pipeline using JUnit XML output
- Use @wdio/spec-reporter for local development feedback

## CI/CD Integration
- Run tests in headless mode in CI environments
- Use docker-compose with selenium-hub for containerized grid
- Parallelize with maxInstances and shard strategies
- Cache node_modules and wdio binaries between runs

## Documentation
- Document custom commands added to browser object
- Maintain a README with setup, run, and debug instructions
- Include examples of common patterns (auth, API mocking, file upload)
- Document environment variable requirements in .env.example

Remember to leverage WebdriverIO's auto-waiting and expect-webdriverio's built-in retry
mechanisms to write stable, low-maintenance tests.
